            "answer": "Yes, we are fully licensed and carry comprehensive liability and workers compensation insurance to protect your property."
      }
],
    commonIssues: [
      "Storm damage",
      "Hazardous conditions",
      "Property encroachment",
      "Safety concerns"
],
    longContent: {
      "intro": "Fallen Tree Removal requires professional expertise to ensure safety and prevent property damage.",
      "methodology": "We use industry-leading techniques and equipment tailored to each specific job.",
      "localAdvice": "South Carolina homeowners should always choose local experts who understand regional soil and climate conditions.",
      "seasonalConsiderations": "Our services are available year-round, with priority emergency response during storm seasons.",
      "homeownerProblems": "We solve complex tree and land issues quickly, safely, and cost-effectively."
},
    image: '/images/services/fallen-tree-removal.webp',
    hasContent: true,
    fullBodyHtml: "<p>A fallen tree in your yard, driveway, or against your home is a serious safety and access hazard that needs to be addressed immediately. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts removes fallen trees of any size, anywhere in South Carolina — safely, efficiently, and with full debris cleanup included. Available 24/7. Call <strong>(888) 643-4199</strong> for a free estimate today.</p>\n<h2>A Fallen Tree Is Never Just an Inconvenience</h2>\n<p>You walked outside this morning, and there it was — a mature Water Oak across your driveway, a Loblolly Pine through your back fence, or a massive Live Oak limb resting against the side of your house. It may not have made the kind of dramatic crash you expected. Sometimes they come down quietly overnight, and you only discover the damage in the morning light.</p>\n<p>Either way, a fallen tree on your property is not a situation that resolves itself. It is a hazard, an access problem, a potential structural threat, and — depending on how it fell — one of the most dangerous objects on your property until it is professionally removed.</p>\n<p>South Carolina&#39;s combination of dense residential tree canopy, high annual rainfall, and long storm seasons means fallen tree calls are among the most common emergency responses our crews handle across the state. </p>\n<p>Saturated soil after a heavy rain event loosens root systems that have held for decades. A summer thunderstorm with a single strong wind gust is enough to bring down a tree that showed no visible signs of distress the day before.</p>\n<p>It happens fast, it happens without warning, and when it does, the tree does not get smaller the longer it sits there.</p>\n<h2>Why a Fallen Tree on Your Property Demands Immediate Attention</h2>\n<p>A tree that has already fallen might seem like the danger is over — the worst has happened, the crash is done, and nothing else can go wrong. That assumption is one of the most common and costly mistakes South Carolina homeowners make after a tree comes down.</p>\n<p>Here is what is actually happening on your property while that fallen tree sits waiting:</p>\n<p><strong>Hung trees are the most unpredictable hazard in tree removal.</strong> When a falling tree does not reach the ground cleanly — catching instead on another tree, a fence, a roofline, or a utility structure — it creates what professionals call a &quot;hung tree&quot; or &quot;widow-maker.&quot; A hung tree is under enormous and constantly shifting tension, and it can complete its fall without any additional wind, rain, or external force — just the slow settling of weight finding its lowest point.</p>\n<p><strong>Root ball upheaval destabilizes the surrounding ground.</strong> When a large tree falls and pulls its root system partially out of the ground, the upheaval creates an unstable void beneath the soil surface. The surrounding ground can shift, sink, or collapse — creating a hidden hazard for anyone walking near the fallen tree, particularly children.</p>\n<p><strong>A fallen tree across a driveway or access route creates dangerous secondary risks.</strong> A blocked driveway is not just an inconvenience — it prevents emergency vehicles from reaching your home if a medical or fire emergency develops while the tree is in place. It also traps vehicles you may urgently need and can create liability issues if the blockage affects neighboring properties or shared access routes.</p>\n<p><strong>Decomposing wood attracts pests that spread to your home.</strong> A fallen tree left on your property begins decomposing almost immediately — and decomposing wood is one of the most attractive environments for termites, carpenter ants, and wood-boring beetles in South Carolina. These are not pests that stay in the log — they move, and the closest wooden structure to that fallen tree is your home.</p>\n<p><strong>Damage to underground utilities can go undetected.</strong> When a large tree falls and pulls its root system from the ground, the root mass can shift, crack, or sever underground water lines, drainage pipes, or buried electrical conduit running beneath your yard. Left unaddressed, a damaged line beneath a fallen tree can become a significantly more expensive problem than the removal itself.</p>\n<p>According to the <a href=\"https://www.fs.usda.gov/\">USDA Forest Service</a>, fallen and hanging trees represent some of the highest-risk post-storm hazards on residential properties — a risk that increases rather than decreases as time passes without professional intervention. In South Carolina, where rainfall keeps soil saturated for extended periods and storm seasons are long, that window of compounding risk is wider than in most other states.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.scemd.org/\">SC Emergency Management Division</a> advises South Carolina homeowners to address storm-related property hazards promptly — not only for personal safety but to protect the validity of insurance claims that depend on reasonable mitigation efforts being made in a timely manner.</p>\n<p>Leaving a fallen tree in place is never a neutral decision. Every day it stays, the list of consequences grows longer.</p>\n<h2>Professional Fallen Tree Removal — Done Right, Done Safely</h2>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts removes fallen trees of every size, in every situation, across all of South Carolina. Whether it is a single downed limb blocking your driveway or a full-canopy Water Oak that came out of the ground roots and all — we have the equipment, the experience, and the crew to handle it safely and efficiently.</p>\n<p>We do not just show up with a chainsaw and start cutting. Every fallen tree removal begins with a professional assessment of the full situation — because how a tree fell, where it landed, and what it is resting against determines the correct removal approach before a single cut is made.</p>\n<h3>How We Remove Fallen Trees in South Carolina</h3>\n<p>Our fallen tree removal process is deliberate, methodical, and designed to protect your property at every stage.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1 — Scene Assessment:</strong> We evaluate the full situation on arrival — is the tree hung up on a structure, fence, or another tree? Is there root-ball upheaval causing ground instability? Are there power lines involved? Nothing moves until the scene is fully understood.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2 — Hazard Identification and Securing</strong> We identify every secondary hazard the fallen tree has created — unstable root voids, hanging limbs, structural contact points — and address them before removal work begins.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3 — Sectional Cutting</strong> We work from the top of the tree downward, cutting in controlled sections rather than attempting to move or drag the tree as a whole. This protects your lawn, your fencing, your driveway, and any structures the tree is resting against.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 4 — Root Ball Removal</strong> If the tree fell with its root system intact and partially lifted from the ground, we address the root ball removal separately — filling and leveling the void left behind to restore ground stability.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 5 — Full Debris Removal and Cleanup:</strong> Every branch, every limb, every piece of wood and debris comes off your property. We do not consider the job finished until your yard is completely clear and your access routes are fully restored.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 6 — Wood Sectioning on Request</strong> If you would like to keep the wood for firewood or other use, we will section the trunk and larger limbs to your preferred length before we leave. If not, full haul-away is included as standard.</p>\n<h3>What About the Stump?</h3>\n<p>When a tree falls and is removed, the stump and root system remain in the ground unless specifically addressed. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts offers stump grinding as part of any fallen tree removal job — eliminating the remaining stump to ground level and removing the last visible trace of the fallen tree from your property.</p>\n<p>Ask about stump grinding when you call — we will include it in your free estimate so you have a complete picture of the full job cost before work begins.</p>\n<h3>Crane-Assisted Fallen Tree Removal — When Standard Removal Is Not Enough</h3>\n<p>Some fallen tree situations require more than ground-based cutting alone. When a large tree has come to rest against a structure, is partially suspended above a vehicle, or has fallen in a location where sectional cutting creates unacceptable risk, crane-assisted removal is the correct approach.</p>\n<p>Our crane capability allows us to lift entire tree sections vertically and away from your property — protecting structures, vehicles, and landscaping that would otherwise be at risk from a standard ground-based removal approach. After 38 years in South Carolina, we know exactly when a crane is the right call — and we have one ready to deploy.</p>\n<h3>We Handle Fallen Trees on Every Property Type</h3>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts removes fallen trees from every type of property across the state. Residential front and back yards, commercial parking lots and business properties, rental properties and HOA communities, rural acreage and wooded lots — if a tree came down on it, we can remove it.</p>\n<p>No property is too large, and no fallen tree situation is too complicated for our crew to assess and handle. We bring the right equipment to every job — and 38 years of experience in knowing which equipment is.</p>\n<h2>The Company South Carolina Trusts to Remove Fallen Trees the Right Way</h2>\n<p>Hiring someone to remove a fallen tree from your property is not the same as hiring someone to mow your lawn or clean your gutters. A fallen tree removal — particularly one involving a structure, a vehicle, a fence line, or an unstable root system — is a high-stakes job where the difference between a professional crew and an unqualified one can be measured in thousands of dollars of additional property damage.</p>\n<p>South Carolina homeowners have trusted South Carolina Tree Removal Experts with that responsibility for 38 years — and that trust has been earned one job at a time.</p>\n<h3>38 Years of Fallen Tree Removal Experience Across South Carolina</h3>\n<p>When we say 38 years of experience, we are not talking about 38 years of general landscaping with some tree work mixed in. We are talking about 38 years of dedicated tree removal — thousands of fallen tree jobs across every region of South Carolina, in every soil type, every property configuration, and every scenario this state&#39;s long storm seasons can produce.</p>\n<p>Our crews have removed fallen Loblolly Pines from rooftops in Columbia, lifted downed Live Oak limbs off vehicles in Charleston, cleared root-ball upheavals from residential lawns in Greenville, and handled post-hurricane fallen tree volume along the Grand Strand that most tree services in this state simply do not have the capacity to manage. That depth of real-world, on-the-ground experience in South Carolina is something no amount of equipment or marketing can substitute for.</p>\n<p>Experience in fallen tree removal specifically means our crews read a scene correctly from the moment they arrive. They identify tension points in a hung tree before making the first cut. They recognize when a root void presents a ground stability risk before anyone walks near it. They know when a standard ground-based approach is appropriate and when a crane is the only safe option — and they make that call based on decades of experience, not guesswork.</p>\n<p>That judgment is what you are hiring when you call South Carolina Tree Removal Experts. It is the most valuable thing we bring to every job.</p>\n<h3>Fully Licensed and Insured — Protecting You From the First Cut to the Last</h3>\n<p>Fallen tree removal carries real liability — and that liability needs to rest with the contractor, not the homeowner. If an uninsured crew causes additional damage to your home, your vehicle, or your neighbor&#39;s property during a removal, you are the one left navigating the financial and legal consequences. That is an entirely avoidable situation when you hire a properly licensed and insured contractor.</p>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts carries full licensing and insurance coverage on every job we perform in South Carolina. Our coverage protects your property throughout the entire removal process — from the moment our crew steps onto your lot to the moment the last piece of debris leaves it. There are no gaps in our coverage, no fine print exclusions for emergency work, and no scenarios where you are left unprotected.</p>\n<p>Before you let any crew touch a fallen tree on your property — especially after a storm when unlicensed operators are actively seeking work — ask to see proof of licensing and insurance. A legitimate, professional tree service will provide it without hesitation. We always do.</p>\n<h3>We Treat Your Property With the Same Care We Would Our Own</h3>\n<p>Fallen tree removal can cause secondary damage — to lawns, landscaping, fencing, driveways, and structures — if not approached with the right level of care. Dragging sections of a large tree across a lawn tears up turf. Dropping cut sections without proper rigging damages fencing and hardscaping. Working too fast on a hung tree can cause unpredictable movement that may shift the tree onto whatever it was resting against.</p>\n<p>We do not work that way. Every cut we make is planned. Every section we remove is controlled. We use protective measures — ground cover for heavy equipment, careful rigging for sections near structures, deliberate sequencing for hung trees — because your property deserves to look as good after the removal as the situation allows.</p>\n<p>After 38 years of fallen tree removals across South Carolina, protecting the property we are working on is as automatic to our crews as the removal itself. It is not an extra service or an upsell — it is simply how we work.</p>\n<h3>Transparent Pricing — Free Estimates Before Any Work Begins</h3>\n<p>We know that a fallen tree on your property is already a stressful and potentially expensive situation. The last thing you need is a contractor who uses that stress to justify unclear, inflated, or sprung-on pricing after the work is done.</p>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts provides a free, detailed estimate before any fallen tree removal work begins — no exceptions, no pressure, no obligation. We walk you through exactly what the job involves, the equipment we will use, the full scope of cleanup, and the total cost before a single chainsaw starts. You approve the estimate, we do the work, and the final bill matches what we quoted.</p>\n<p>That transparency is a standard we have maintained for 38 years — because a company that is genuinely confident in the quality of its work does not need to hide its pricing.</p>\n<h3>Documentation for Your Insurance Claim — Handled</h3>\n<p>If your fallen tree is the result of a storm event, your homeowners&#39; insurance policy may cover part or all of the removal cost — particularly if the tree came down on a covered structure. Getting that claim processed smoothly requires proper documentation of the damage before and during removal.</p>\n<p>Our crews photograph and document every fallen tree job from arrival through completion. We record the pre-removal state of the tree and surrounding property, the removal process itself, and the post-removal condition of your yard and any affected structures. That documentation package is yours to use however you need it — for your insurance claim, for a contractor assessing structural damage, or simply for your own records.</p>\n<p>We have supported South Carolina homeowners through the insurance claim process after fallen tree events more times than we can count. We know what your insurer needs to see, and we make sure you have it.</p>\n<h3>A Company With 38 Years of Reputation to Protect</h3>\n<p>There is one more dimension of trust that is worth stating plainly. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts has operated in this state for 38 years — and in nearly four decades, our reputation has been built entirely on the quality of our work and the experience of our customers. We are not a franchise operation; we are not managing your call from a regional headquarters. We are not a storm-chasing crew that arrived after the last hurricane and will be gone before the next one.</p>\n<p>We are a South Carolina company with 38 years of reputation invested in every single job we take. That reputation is not something we are willing to compromise for any reason, which means every fallen tree removal we perform gets the same level of care, professionalism, and attention to detail that has kept South Carolina homeowners calling us for nearly four decades.</p>\n<h2>South Carolina&#39;s Fallen Tree Problem — and Why Local Experience Matters</h2>\n<p>Fallen trees are not a generic problem with a generic solution. The species that falls, the soil it fell in, the storm that brought it down, and the property it landed on are all specific to South Carolina — and handling them correctly requires experience that is just as specific.</p>\n<p>After 38 years of working across every region of this state, South Carolina Tree Removal Experts understands South Carolina&#39;s fallen tree landscape better than any out-of-state company ever could.</p>\n<h3>Why South Carolina Properties See So Many Fallen Trees</h3>\n<p>South Carolina&#39;s combination of climate, soil conditions, and tree species creates a fallen tree risk profile that is higher than most homeowners fully appreciate. Understanding why trees fall in this state is the first step toward understanding why professional removal matters so much when they do.</p>\n<p>South Carolina receives an average of 44 to 55 inches of rainfall per year, depending on the region, significantly above the national average. That sustained moisture keeps soil saturated for extended periods, particularly in the Lowcountry and Midlands, where clay-heavy soils drain slowly. </p>\n<p>Saturated soil dramatically reduces the anchoring strength of a tree&#39;s root system — which is why so many of the fallen tree calls we receive across South Carolina happen not during the peak of a storm, but in the days immediately after one, when the ground is at its wettest and root systems are at their most vulnerable.</p>\n<p>South Carolina&#39;s long growing season also means trees grow fast — which sounds like a positive until you understand that fast-growing species like Loblolly Pine and Water Oak often develop root systems that do not keep pace with their above-ground growth. A 70-foot Loblolly Pine in a Columbia backyard may have a surprisingly shallow root footprint for its height, making it far more vulnerable to wind and saturated soil than its size suggests.</p>\n<p>Add to this the reality of South Carolina&#39;s storm seasons — six months of hurricane risk on the coast, year-round severe thunderstorm exposure inland, and ice storm risk in the Upstate — and the picture becomes clear. Fallen trees are not uncommon in South Carolina. They are a predictable consequence of living in one of the most beautifully treed states in the country.</p>\n<h3>Fallen Tree Scenarios We Encounter Across South Carolina</h3>\n<p>Different regions of South Carolina produce different fallen tree situations — and our crews know exactly what to expect in each one.</p>\n<p>In the <strong>Lowcountry</strong>, the most common fallen tree scenarios involve Southern Live Oaks and Loblolly Pines coming down during hurricane and tropical storm events. Live Oak limb failures are particularly challenging — the limbs are enormously heavy, often suspended above structures or vehicles, and require precision sectional removal that demands both the right equipment and the right experience. Charleston, Mount Pleasant, Summerville, and Beaufort homeowners face this reality every hurricane season.</p>\n<p>In the <strong>Midlands</strong>, Water Oak root failures after summer storm saturation events are the single most common cause of fallen trees our crews respond to. Columbia, Lexington, and West Columbia sit in a corridor where fast-moving thunderstorms saturate already clay-heavy soils — and Water Oaks that have stood for thirty years come out of the ground seemingly overnight. </p>\n<p>The root ball upheaval these failures create is significant, and restoring ground stability after removal is as important as the removal itself.</p>\n<p>Along the <strong>Grand Strand</strong>, coastal Myrtle Beach, North Myrtle Beach, and Conway properties face a unique combination of sandy soil instability and hurricane-force winds that make tree root systems particularly vulnerable. Sandy coastal soils provide far less anchoring strength than inland soils — meaning trees in beachside and near-coastal communities fall at lower wind speeds than the same species would inland. </p>\n<p>Vacation rental property owners and HOA communities along the Grand Strand know this reality well and who to call when a tree comes down.</p>\n<p>In the <strong>Upstate</strong>, homeowners in Greenville, Spartanburg, and Anderson face fallen trees driven primarily by ice storms and severe wind events rather than saturated soil. Ice-loaded Sweetgums and Tulip Poplars are among the most common fallen tree species our Upstate crews encounter — trees that came down under the sheer weight of overnight ice accumulation rather than wind or root failure. </p>\n<p>The cleanup after an Upstate ice event is extensive, and our crews are equipped and experienced to handle the volume.</p>\n<p>Across the <strong>Pee Dee region</strong>, properties in Florence, Darlington, and Hartsville experience a mix of storm-driven Loblolly Pine failures and Water Oak root collapses, keeping our crews active throughout the spring and summer storm season. The Pee Dee&#39;s flat topography and heavy rainfall totals create ideal conditions for prolonged soil saturation that precedes many of the region&#39;s most significant fallen tree events.</p>\n<h3>Serving Every South Carolina Community With the Same Standard of Care</h3>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts responds to fallen tree calls across every region and every community in South Carolina. From the coastal communities of Hilton Head, Bluffton, and Beaufort to the Upstate cities of Greenville, Spartanburg, and Anderson — from Columbia, Lexington, and the Midlands corridor to Myrtle Beach, Conway, and the Grand Strand — we bring the same equipment, the same experience, and the same standard of professional care to every property we work on.</p>\n<p>We serve homeowners, landlords, property managers, HOA communities, commercial property owners, and developers across the state. No fallen tree situation is too remote, too large, or too complicated for our crews to assess and handle — because after 38 years serving South Carolina, we have seen and handled all of it before.</p>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts is not a company that learned its trade somewhere else and set up shop here. We were built in South Carolina, trained on South Carolina&#39;s trees and soils, and storms, and have spent 38 years developing the local knowledge that makes the difference between a removal that protects your property and one that creates new problems while solving the old ones.</p>\n<h2>Fallen Tree Removal FAQs</h2>\n<p><em>The questions South Carolina homeowners ask us most about fallen tree removal — answered directly so you know exactly what to expect when you call.</em></p>\n<h3>How Much Does Fallen Tree Removal Cost in South Carolina?</h3>\n<p>Fallen tree removal costs in South Carolina vary based on several factors — the size and species of the tree, where it landed, whether it is in contact with a structure or vehicle, the equipment required for safe removal, and your location within the state.</p>\n<p> A small fallen limb blocking a driveway is a very different job from a full-canopy Water Oak that came out of the ground, roots and all, and landed against your home. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts provides a free, detailed on-site estimate before any work begins — so you know the full cost and agree to it before our crew starts. Call <strong>(888) 643-4199</strong> to schedule your free estimate today.</p>\n<h3>Who Is Responsible for a Fallen Tree — Me or My Neighbor?</h3>\n<p>Tree liability in South Carolina generally follows the property line — meaning if a tree falls from your neighbor&#39;s yard onto your property, your homeowners&#39; insurance is typically the first line of coverage for the damage to your property, regardless of where the tree originated. </p>\n<p>If your neighbor&#39;s tree was visibly dead, diseased, or hazardous and they were notified of the risk prior to the fall, liability may shift — but this is a legal question that depends entirely on the specific circumstances and your policy terms. </p>\n<p>We recommend contacting your insurance provider immediately after any fallen tree event and consulting a legal professional if a neighbor&#39;s tree is involved. What we can tell you with certainty is that South Carolina Tree Removal Experts will remove the tree safely, document everything thoroughly, and make sure you have the records you need for whatever comes next.</p>\n<h3>What If the Fallen Tree Is Touching a Power Line?</h3>\n<p>If a fallen tree on your property is in contact with a power line — whether a line running to your home or a utility line along the street — treat the entire area as a live electrical hazard until your utility provider has confirmed otherwise. Do not approach the tree, do not attempt to move it, and keep everyone — including pets — well clear of the tree, the line, and the ground surrounding both. </p>\n<p>Contact your utility provider immediately and let them de-energize the line before any removal work begins. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts will not begin work on any fallen tree that is in contact with an active power line until utility crews have confirmed it is safe to do so — this is a non-negotiable safety standard we maintain on every job, every time.</p>\n<h3>How Long Does Fallen Tree Removal Take in South Carolina?</h3>\n<p>The time required to remove a fallen tree depends on the tree&#39;s size, its position, and the scope of debris cleanup. A straightforward fallen limb or small tree in an open yard can often be cleared within a few hours. </p>\n<p>A large Loblolly Pine or Live Oak that came down against a structure, requires crane-assisted removal, or involves significant root ball work, may take a full day or longer to remove completely and safely. South Carolina Tree Removal Experts will give you a realistic timeframe as part of your free estimate — so you know what to expect before we begin and can plan accordingly.</p>\n<h3>Do You Haul Away All the Wood and Debris After Removing a Fallen Tree?</h3>\n<p>Yes — full debris removal and haul-away is included as standard on every fallen tree removal job we perform. We do not leave piles of cut wood, brush, or debris on your property for you to deal with after we leave. </p>\n<p>Every branch, every limb, and every piece of debris comes off your property as part of the job. If you would like to keep the wood sectioned for firewood or otherwise, just let us know when you call, and we will accommodate that preference. If not, everything goes with us, and your yard is left completely clear.</p>\n<h3>Can You Remove a Fallen Tree That Is Partially Hanging in Another Tree?</h3>\n<p>Yes — and this is one of the most important fallen tree scenarios to address urgently. A partially fallen tree that is hung up in another tree is under significant and unpredictable tension — it can shift or complete its fall without warning at any time. </p>\n<p>Our crews are trained and equipped specifically for hung tree removal, using rigging and controlled cutting techniques to safely release the tension and bring the tree down in a controlled sequence rather than allowing it to fall freely. Never attempt to pull, push, or cut a hung tree yourself — the forces involved are far greater than they appear, and the consequences of an uncontrolled release can be severe. </p>\n<p>Call South Carolina Tree Removal Experts at <strong>(888) 643-4199</strong> for immediate assessment of any hung or partially fallen tree on your property.</p>\n<h2>Tree Down in South Carolina? We Are Ready to Remove It — Right Now</h2>\n<p>A fallen tree on your property is not something that gets easier with time. The longer it sits, the longer your driveway stays blocked, the longer your fence stays damaged, the longer the risk of a hung section completing its fall remains, and the longer South Carolina&#39;s insects and humidity have to begin their work on the wood.</p>\n<p>The right move is a simple one — call the company that has been removing fallen trees across South Carolina for 38 years and let us handle it from start to finish.</p>\n<p>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts answers the phone 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. We dispatch without delay, arrive equipped for whatever we find, remove the tree safely and completely, haul away every piece of debris, and leave your property clear. From the first call to the final cleanup — you are in experienced, professional, fully insured hands.</p>\n<p>It does not matter how big the tree is. It does not matter how it fell or where it landed. It does not matter what time you are reading this. We are ready right now.</p>\n<p><strong>One call is all it takes.</strong></p>\n<p>📞 <strong>Call (888) 643-4199 — 24/7 Fallen Tree Removal Across South Carolina.</strong> Free estimates. Licensed and insured. Full debris cleanup included. No voicemail. No waiting.</p>\n<p><em>South Carolina Tree Removal Experts — South Carolina&#39;s most experienced fallen tree removal company since 1986.</em></p>"
  },
